            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Arman Khoury\u2019s life is a study in bridging worlds. Born in Daly City to Lebanese-Armenian immigrants, his childhood was steeped in the rich aromas of his mother\u2019s kitchen and the warm, boisterous hospitality of his father\u2019s small import goods store. He watched his parents create a community hub, not just a business, learning early that commerce was less about transactions and more about connection. This foundational lesson became the quiet engine of his ambition.\n\nDrawn to the city\u2019s vibrant energy, Arman attended San Francisco State University, pursuing a Marketing degree to put a modern framework on the old-world skills he\u2019d inherited. Post-graduation, he landed a role at a fast-growing, direct-to-consumer home goods brand with a flagship store in Hayes Valley. He excelled, but felt a disconnect; he wasn\u2019t just selling minimalist linen sheets, he was selling the idea of a serene home. After two years, he drafted and successfully pitched a new role for himself: Experience Manager. His job now is to choreograph the in-store journey, from the ambient playlist and subtle scent diffusers to staff training focused on intuitive, low-pressure guidance.\n\nHis daily routine is quintessentially San Francisco. He starts his day with a foggy run in Golden Gate Park before catching a crowded Muni bus from his shared Inner Richmond apartment for the 3.8-mile commute. His income of $85,000 affords him a comfortable but not extravagant lifestyle, where dinners with his close circle of college friends are more likely at a Clement Street noodle house than a fine-dining establishment.\n\nArman\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deep. He loves the city's mosaic of cultures, which reminds him of his own layered identity. While he is proud of his professional success, a dream is beginning to crystallize. He envisions opening his own space one day\u2014not just a store, but a modern community hub. A place that combines the clean aesthetic of his current work with the soul-deep, welcoming spirit of his parents\u2019 shop, proving that genuine human connection is the ultimate luxury good."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, stacking tins of za'atar in his father's Daly City store. He remembers watching his dad spend twenty minutes with Mrs. Yerevan, not just selling her olive oil, but listening to stories about her son. There was no pressure, only patience and a shared pot of cardamom coffee. In that moment, Arman understood. The goods were just an excuse for the gathering. The true business was community, a lesson that settled deep in his bones and would later define his entire career.\n\n2.\nHis freshman year at SF State, he sat on a bench near the student union, overwhelmed. He heard snippets of Cantonese, Spanish, and Russian, saw punk kids sharing lunch with students in hijabs. It wasn't a melting pot; it was a mosaic, each piece distinct yet part of a beautiful whole. For the first time, his own layered identity didn't feel complicated, it felt like it belonged. He wasn't just from Daly City; he was *of* San Francisco. It cemented his love for the city's complex soul.\n\n3.\nHe was arranging minimalist duvet covers in the quiet Hayes Valley store, the air scented with a generic \"calm\" fragrance. A customer bought a $400 sheet set without making eye contact. He felt a sudden, hollow ache\u2014a profound disconnect from his father\u2019s warm, bustling shop. That evening, fueled by frustration and cheap coffee, he didn\u2019t just draft a new job description for an 'Experience Manager.' He drafted a mission statement for himself, a bridge between cold aesthetics and the human connection he craved.\n\n4.\nJust last week, on a pre-dawn run in Golden Gate Park, the fog was so thick it swallowed the sound of the city. He stopped near the Dutch Windmill, the cool, damp air filling his lungs. In that quiet, solitary moment, hearing only his own heartbeat and the distant foghorns, he felt utterly anonymous and completely at home. This ritual isn\u2019t about fitness; it\u2019s about recalibrating his soul before facing the day, a reminder of the peace that exists within the city's constant hum.\n\n5.\nA few months ago, huddled over steaming bowls of ramen on Clement Street with his college friends, the laughter was easy and loud. He looked around the packed, no-frills noodle house\u2014the shared tables, the efficient chaos, the genuine joy. It hit him with the force of a revelation. This was it. This feeling was the luxury good. His future shop wouldn\u2019t just have beautiful objects; it would have this sound. The sound of connection. The blueprint for his dream crystallized in that warm, noisy room."
